---
export const prerender = false;

import ToolPageLayout from '../../../layouts/ToolPageLayout.astro';
import { P2PShare } from '../../../components/P2PShare';

const { roomId } = Astro.params;

const faqs = [
  {
    question: "Where are my files stored during transfer?",
    answer: "Nowhere but your own devices. The files are not uploaded to any server. They are read into the sender's browser memory as chunks, sent over a direct encrypted WebRTC link, and compiled into memory by the receiver's browser."
  },
  {
    question: "Can I close the sender browser tab?",
    answer: "No. Because the file transfer is active peer-to-peer, closing either the sender or receiver tab will terminate the connection immediately. Both browsers must remain active and open until the transaction reaches 100% completion."
  },
  {
    question: "Why is the connection failing or stuck at \"Connecting\"?",
    answer: "WebRTC requires establishing a direct IP-to-IP path. If both devices are behind symmetric NAT routers (very common in corporate networks or guest Wi-Fi networks), they cannot discover a direct route without a TURN relay. If this happens, try switching both devices to the same local network, or use a cellular hotspot to bypass strict firewall configurations."
  },
  {
    question: "Can I transfer multiple files at once?",
    answer: "Currently, our P2P sharing utility supports transferring one file at a time per room connection. If you need to share multiple files, we recommend compiling them into a single archive format (like `.zip`, `.tar.gz`, or `.rar`) on your machine before dropping it into the workspace."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the maximum file size limit for WebRTC transfers?",
    answer: "Technically, there is no hard file size limit since the data is streamed as continuous binary chunks. However, because modern browsers store the incoming chunks in the browser's temporary memory (RAM) buffer, transfers are limited by the receiver's available system memory. For a smooth experience, we recommend files up to 1GB."
  },
  {
    question: "Is 1-to-many P2P file sharing supported?",
    answer: "Yes! Our tool fully supports 1-to-many sharing. A single sender can generate a room and share the link with multiple receivers. The sender's browser will open independent WebRTC peer connections with each receiver, streaming the file to them simultaneously. Each receiver's transfer runs at its own optimal speed based on their network capability."
  },
  {
    question: "How is the file transfer speed determined in WebRTC?",
    answer: "Transfer speed depends entirely on the network bandwidth of both the sender and the receiver. Because WebRTC establishes a direct path, if both devices are on the same local network (LAN) or Wi-Fi, the speeds can reach the maximum rate of your local hardware (often 100 Mbps to 1 Gbps+), completely bypassing external internet speeds. If transferring over the internet (WAN), the speed is capped by the sender's upload bandwidth and the receiver's download bandwidth."
  },
  {
    question: "Does this tool require active internet connection once the transfer starts?",
    answer: "Yes and no. The initial handshake (exchanging SDP profiles and ICE candidate routes) requires connection to our signaling server, which runs on the internet. Once the browsers establish the direct peer-to-peer WebRTC connection, all file data flows directly between them. If both devices are in the same local network, you could theoretically unplug the external internet connection, and the local P2P transfer will continue uninterrupted."
  },
  {
    question: "Is my data safe from network eavesdroppers or ISPs?",
    answer: "Absolutely. WebRTC uses mandatory DTLS (Datagram Transport Layer Security) and SRTP (Secure Real-time Transport Protocol) encryption for all data channels. This means the file streams are encrypted end-to-end with keys generated dynamically during the initial handshake. Not even our signaling server, your network administrator, or your ISP can inspect, read, or tamper with the payloads in transit."
  },
  {
    question: "Can I resume a paused or interrupted transfer?",
    answer: "Since our P2P share tool operates entirely in the browser memory without any server storage, it does not support connection resumption or checkpointing. If the connection drops or a browser tab is accidentally closed, the transfer state is cleared from the browser's temporary memory. You will need to re-open the room link and restart the file transfer from the beginning."
  }
];
---

<ToolPageLayout
  title="Receive File Privately: Secure P2P WebRTC Transfer"
  description="Receive files directly inside your browser over an encrypted, peer-to-peer WebRTC data channel with zero server retention or transit logs."
  keywords="p2p file sharing, receive files directly, secure file transfer, private file sharing online, webrtc receiver"
  noindex={true}
  toolTitle="P2P File Share"
  toolDescription="Secure, client-side peer-to-peer file sharing. Your files are encrypted in transit and streamed directly between browsers using WebRTC with zero server storage."
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <P2PShare client:only="react" roomId={roomId} />

  <!-- Detailed SEO articles about receiving P2P WebRTC file transfers -->
  <div slot="seo-content" class="flex flex-col gap-8">
    <!-- Section: Intro -->
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-50 tracking-tight mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
        <span class="w-1.5 h-6 bg-accent-emerald rounded-full"></span>
        Receiving Files Safely Point-to-Point
      </h2>
      <p class="text-zinc-400 text-sm leading-relaxed font-sans mb-4">
        You have accessed a secure, direct file transfer room. When you load this page, your browser automatically connects to a temporary signaling server to coordinates a WebRTC handshake with the sender.
      </p>
      <p class="text-zinc-400 text-sm leading-relaxed font-sans">
        Once the connection is established, the sender will read the file and stream it directly into your browser using standard, secure datagram tunnels. Absolutely zero data goes to a server, and the file is compiled dynamically inside your local browser memory sandbox.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</ToolPageLayout>
